 Anon's tests with SCM, but with plain old 200 specialization I can guarantee your savings are 10% each and every cast, no more, no less.<br>
<br>
Anyone have SCM3 yet and can run some tests? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/24/02 6:29 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: You tell em fasty!</span><hr size=1> I'll back up those stating a 10% to 12% constant reduction at 200 spec.  I did a series of tests on this a year ago.  I would drop my mana below the listed mana and attempt to cast until the spell went off.  At that point I knew I had the listed mana (no calculations necessary), no more, no less.  After the spell went off, I then attempted to cast lower mana spells to bracket how much mana was left.  I couldn't be as precise as someone using ShowEQ, but I found it to be in the 10% to 13% range.<br>
<br>
So, yes, at 200 specialization, there is a fixed % reduction in the mana cost, which is done at the time the spell is successfully cast.  It doesn't vary. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/umerloc.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Merloc</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><table width=111><tr><td style=filter:glow(color=#6633FF strength=1);font-family:arial;font-weight;bold;font-size:'1pt' nowrap><font size=1 color=#FFFFFF face=Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif>Site Sorcerer</font></td></tr></table></span><br>  Posts: 159<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/25/02 3:12 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://faust.ece.ubc.ca/merloc/merlocface2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Merloc's SCM Tests</span><hr size=1> I did some tests today with 2 level 60 wizards with identical equipment and base int.<br>
<br>
Both wizards had 206 int,  355 mana, and epic effect on.<br>
<br>
I used draught of ice for the tests.<br>
<br>
Wizard 1: Erikkin, MC: 3, SCM: 0<br>
Wizard 2: Merloc, MC: 3, SCM: 3<br>
<br>
Test 1: FM to insufficient mana.<br>
Wizard 1: 14 casts (1 fizzle)<br>
Wizard 2: 17 casts<br>
21.4% mana increase, (less if you count the fizzle)<br>
<br>
Test 2: FM to insufficient mana.<br>
Wizard 1: 15 casts<br>
Wizard 2: 17 casts<br>
13.3% mana increase<br>
<br>
Test 3: FM to simultaneous insufficient mana and 2 extra rounds of synchronized medding (and c3).<br>
Wizard 1: 55 casts<br>
Wizard 2: 63 casts (1 fizzle)<br>
14.5% mana increase, (slightly more counting fizzle)<br>
<br>
The last test was very accurate, and if you count the fizzle it is just about 15% mana increase.<br>
<br>
I am guessing that as your specialization skill increases, the amount of mana you save increases (when you make your specialization check) up to 50% mana savings.  If you assume that SCM: 3 increases your chance of specialization by an extra 30%, you can do the math and come up with a 15% mana savings overall, which is the number I got from my tests.<br>
<br>
Merloc <p><CENTER>
