<br>
MC3 gives you from 15-7% increase depending on if you have epic and how many FT items you have. The effect of MC will diminish as you acquire FT items. If you continually run with C2 or Koadic's then it is even less beneficial.<br>
<br>
SCM3 gives a straight 10% (and I haven't done my own calcs yet just taking fasty's #) but it is always 10% and doesn't taper out. It also has the added benefit of giving you the 10%in the form of increased total dmg output per mana bar.. IE you can solo 10% larger critters. Whereas MC only lets you solo the same mobs with 15-7% less downtime.<br>
<br>
SCF3 gives 7% and does not taper off. It does not let you solo larger mobs.. because it is not reliable. It is mainly useful in raids and grind groups.<br>
<br>
FK <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utwiddleotoole.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Twiddle OToole</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.eskimo.com/~aiken/eq/Twiddle_OToole_bullet.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>Arrrrghh!!! Ahoy!</span><br>  Posts: 761<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/25/02 1:51 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.eskimo.com/~aiken/eq/twidsm2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Merloc's SCM Tests</span><hr size=1> Here's my experiment, conducted last night, with just base specialization, no SCM:<br>
<br>
I started with one spell to judge the savings on. I picked the biggest-costing evocation spell I have:<br>
<br>
- Supernova (875 mana)<br>
<br>
Then, since we're testing a proposed 10-12% constant savings, I loaded up a few other spells to see how much, in that range, would be left after I cast Supernova:<br>
<br>
- Force Shock (120 mana, 13.7% of Supernova)<br>
- Frost Shock (110 mana, 12.6%)<br>
- Garrison's Mighty Mana Shock (90 mana, 10.3%)<br>
- Project Lighting (85 mana, 9.7%)<br>
- Flame Shock (75 mana, 8.6%)<br>
<br>
I first cast a junk spell until I got myself just below being able to cast Supernova. Then I kept clicking it, and my flux staff to keep mana count up-to-date, until my standing regen (2 mana/tick with MC1) got me above 875 mana and Supernova started to go off. I clicked my stopwatch the second Supernova began to cast.<br>
<br>
Immediately after successfully casting Supernova, I started clicking Force Shock down through Flame Shock to see how much mana I had left. Garrison's Mighty Mana Shock was the first one I could find that I was able to cast. I quickly interrupted it so as not to actually use the mana, then started clicking the next most expensive one, Frost Shock, until it went off. I then clicked off my stopwatch. At that time I should have had 110 mana. There were 30 seconds between casting Supernova and my being able to cast Frost Shock, so I had regenerated 5 ticks * 2 mana/tick = 10 mana. Do some quick algebra with x being the unknown specialization factor:<br>
<br>
875x + 10 = 110<br>
875x = 100<br>
x = 100 / 875<br>
x = 0.114285714286<br>
<br>
This equates to about an 11.43% savings at Specialize: Evocation of 200.<br>
<br>
I tried this experiment 4 times and got exactly the same result every time. Yes, it's not a big sample size, but it takes a while to regen 875 mana and I'm not gonna spend all night doing it.<br>
<br>
I compared x to my Specialize and it looks like it's derived by specialize / 1750, which gives *exactly* the value above. Where 1750 comes from, I dunno yet.<br>
<br>
I then tried my lesser specializations.<br>
<br>
Extrapolating from the results above, I tried alteration (specialize at 50) with Translocate: Group (600 mana). I calculated that it should leave about 600 * (50 / 1750) = ~17 mana in my pool after specialization. I loaded up Root also (30 mana) and determined that, since it would require 13 more mana, I would require 42 seconds (7 ticks = 14 mana) between the start of casting Translocate: Group and being able to cast Root. I ran the experiment twice and indeed, it was 42 seconds both times.<br>
<br>
I wanted to try with a specialize whose parent skill was not maxed (my evo and alt are both 235), so I naturally picked conjuration, which in my case is 208 with specialize 50. I used Familiar (525 mana), which should leave 15 mana with specialize of 50, and Eye of Zomm (30 mana), which should require 48 more seconds (8 ticks, 16 mana). Again, I ran this twice and got the right results each time. Unfortunately, 208 vs. 235 is not a big difference, so it's hard to say with certainty that parent skill has nothing to do with specialization, but it does appear that way.<br>
<br>
You can infer from all this that the savings is actually (specialize / 1750) * cost, and is constant on every cast even with lower specialize skills.<br>
<br>
I also double-checked, using Force Shock and Greater Shielding (both 120 mana) to be sure that the game checks the full cost of the spell before letting you cast it. I clicked rapidly back and forth between the two while I stood regenerating mana, also fluxing to keep the count accurate, and both became available on the same tick.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
EDIT: I was reading through this and noticed that 1750 = 2 x 875, which was the Supernova cost. I quickly tried specialize / (2 * cost) for the other tests and it doesn't hold true for either the alt or the conj test, so I think it's pure coincidence. That would also make little sense for low-cost spells. Just FYI.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
EDIT 2: Looks like, from Merloc's test, SCM3 adds 200 specialize skill.<br>
<br>
The wizard without SCM3 should have been saving about 11.428 percent on every cast, if my test above was right. To put this in terms of mana pool increase, as Merloc did, that's 1 / (1 - 0.11428) = 1 / 0.88571 = 1.129 = 12.9 percent increase in mana pool. Note that this is the increase over no specialization at all.<br>
<br>
If my supposition about +200 is also right, the wizard with SCM3 was saving 22.857 percent on every cast with sp.evo of 400. To again put this in terms of mana pool increase, that's 1 / (1 - 0.22857) = 1 / 0.77143 = 1.296 = 29.6 percent increase in mana pool. Note again that this is also the increase over no specialization at all.<br>
<br>
Relative to each other, the wizard with SCM3 has 1.296 / 1.129 = 1.148 = 14.8 percent increase in mana pool versus the wizard without. This concurs with Merloc's numbers.<br>
<br>
If SCM is described as 5%, 15% and 30% increases in something, and SCM3 really gives +200 specialization skill (for savings in mana), we can infer that SCM2 probably adds +100 to your specialize and SCM1 might be +30 or +50. Dunno about fizzles.<br>
<br>
---<br>
<br>
EDIT 3: Modified EDIT 2 to reflect +200 instead of x2 as suggested by Fastasia's findings.<br>
